content.description: The crux is at the last bolt and again at last move which can feel delicate.
content.protection: 4 bolts climbing through to chain anchors backed up by webbing
content.location: Route starts on same holds as #3. A peak shaped hold and an under cling to move rightward up low sloping crack. Moves up the side and briefly onto the face and back to arete at last bolt.

content.description: The route climbs a line to right of center on the face and continues up to a right facing corner. Great holds albeit a bit sharp. Crux is after clipping the last bolt and traversing right to chain anchors.
content.protection: Bolts climbing through to chain anchors backed up with webbing.
content.location: Route begins on diamond or "peak" shaped jug and moves left to slightly higher pinch of another "peak" shaped hold. Good feet. High first bolt. 4 bolts to chain anchors above right most arete.

content.description: The crux is leaving the ground and the first two moves to gain the obvious ledge.
content.protection: Bolts climbing through to chain anchors
content.location: Route# 2 begins on two jugs, one each facing left and right and about 10 feet from Route# 1. These two jugs are below and in line with the first obvious bolt. You'll know you're in the right place when you need to stand up on the start and a high left hand.

content.description: The crux could be the the start, just trying to get a solid stance to begin. Because of the traversing nature the bolts feel a little spaced out.
content.location: Route begins on the far left of the face on left sloping jug/ledge. Route meanders rightward diagonally toward first bolted anchor and ends on chain anchors above Route #2, four bolts. Optionally you could link this with Route 2 or 3 to create a longer meandering traverse.

content.description: The cliff lays just off the trail and a bit up hill to the right. Stay on obvious trail that heads to the left of the face to limit erosion and practice Leave No Trace principles. Bears are in the area; be bear aware. The rock face has a few loose holds and tapping on suspect holds is a good idea. Climbing on the face a few holds and foot holds have broken off.  The cliffs here do not receive direct sunlight due to the dense canopy of the forest.
